://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2000/01/03/national/main145553.shtml \"Serial Murder Suspect Caught\"].  ''[[CBS News]]''.  January 3, 2000. Retrieved August 1, 2007.</ref> In 2005, he left his career in [[journalism]] to pursue [[filmmaking]].<ref>[http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/dxnext/id.72/title.todd-angkasuwan \"Todd Angkasuwan | DXNext\"].  ''HipHopDX''.  July 16, 2008. Retrieved July 27, 2008.</ref>\n\nIn the 2006 film ''[[No Sleep Til Shanghai]]'' (Raptivism/Imperial/Caroline/[[EMI]]), Angkasuwan follows rapper [[Jin Au-Yeung]], the first [[Asian American]] signed to a major [[hip-hop]] label, on an eight-city tour of [[Asia]]. The film documents the experiences of Jin and his entourage in visiting cities like [[Shanghai]], [[Tokyo]], [[Taipei]] and [[Singapore]] for the first time.<ref>[http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117930056.html?categoryid=31&cs=1 \"No Sleep Til Shanghai Review\"].  ''[[Variety.com]]''.  March 28, 2006. Retrieved August 1, 2007.</ref> The film screened to a sold out audience at the 2006 San Francisco International Asian American Film Festival, where it was nominated for Best Documentary.<ref>[http://www.myspace.com/nosleeptilshanghai \"No Sleep Til Shanghai MySpace\"]</ref> It was also nominated for Best Documentary at the 2005 Atlanta Hip Hop Film Festival.<ref>[[No Sleep Til Shanghai|\"No Sleep Til Shanghai Wikipedia page\"]]</ref>\n\nAngkasuwan has written for [[AllHipHop]]<ref name=\"azn\"/><ref>[http://www.allhiphop.com/stories/alternatives/archive/2006/01/24/18135510.aspx \"Dave Meyers: Point Of View\"].  ''[[AllHipHop]]''.  January 24, 2006. Retrieved June 13, 2009.</ref> and cites [[Stanley Kubrick]], [[Wong Kar-wai]], [[Michel Gondry]], [[Hype Williams]] and [[David Fincher]] as influences.<ref>[http://www.dubcnn.com/interviews/toddangkasuwan \"Todd Angkasuwan Interview\"].  ''Dubcnn''. March 2009. Retrieved June 12, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Music videos==\nHis directing work includes music videos for artists including:\n\n2005\n*[[Jin (rapper)|Jin]] - \"[[Top 5 (Dead or Alive)]]\"\n2006\n*The Society of Invisibles - \"Watching You\"\n*Anglo-Saxon - \"This Old House\"\n*Roscoe Umali featuring [[E-40]] - \"Live It Up\"\n*Move.meant - \"Good Money\"\n*Move.meant - \"Higher (Breathe)\"\n*Chan - \"Lonely Road\"\n*[[MC Jin|Jin]] - \"F.Y.I.\"/\"100 Grand Jin\"\n*[[Far*East Movement]] - \"Holla Hey\"\n*The Society of Invisibles - \"Hack Pack\"\n*[[Strong Arm Steady]] feat. [[Talib Kweli]] - \"One Step\"\n*[[Far*East Movement]] - \"Smile\"\n2007\n*[[Joell Ortiz]] - \"125 Grams\"\n*Chan - \"Street Legends\"\n*[[Jin (rapper)|Jin]] - \"[[ABC (Jin song)|ABC]]\"\n*[[Mitchy Slick]] - \"Ain't My Fault\"\n*[[KRS-One]] featuring [[Marley Marl]] - \"[[Hip Hop Lives]]\"\n*[[Bizarre (rapper)|Bizarre]] - \"Fat Boy\"\n*[[Styles P]] feat. [[Swizz Beatz]] - \"[[Blow Ya Mind]]\"\n\n2008\n*Vox Merger - \"Reasons\"\n*[[AZ (rapper)|AZ]] - \"Undeniable\"\n*[[Sheek Louch]] - \"[[Good Love (Sheek Louch song)|Good Love]]\"\n*[[Far*East Movement]] featuring [[Baby Bash]] and [[Lil Rob]] - \"You've Got a Friend\"\n*[[RZA]] feat. [[Inspectah Deck]] - \"Can't Stop Me Now\"\n*[[Wale (rapper)|Wale]] & [[Justice (French band)|Justice]] - \"W.A.L.E.D.A.N.C.E.\"\n*[[Snoop Dogg]]/[[Akshay Kumar]]/[[RDB (Rhythm Dhol Bass)|RDB]]  - \"[[Singh Is Kinng|Singh Is King]]\"\n*[[Slow Pain]]  - \"OG Love\"\n*[[DMX (rapper)|DMX]]  - \"Already\" (Unreleased)<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z3gLlyaps8U&feature=player_embedded \"'BTS for DMX's 'Already' video\"]</ref>\n*Ese Daz  - \"She's Got It\"\n*[[RZA]] feat. Monk & Thea - \"Drama\"\n*[[Snoop Dogg]]  - \"Staxxx in My Jeans\"\n*[[Lil Rob]]  - \"Let Me Come Back\"\n\n2009\n*DJ Revolution ft. Kbimean - \"Man Or Machine\"\n*[[UGK]] - \"Da Game Been Good To Me\"\n*[[B-Real]] ft. [[Damian Marley]] - \"Fire\"\n*[[Reflection Eternal]] ([[Talib Kweli]] & [[Hi-Tek]]) - \"Back Again\"\n*[[Tash (rapper)|Tash]] - \"New Bikini\"\n*[[KRS-One]] & [[Buckshot (rapper)|Buckshot]] - \"Robot\"\n*Marco Polo & Torae - \"